[3] New York (Westchester County): coyote, human exposure
Date: Tue 1 May 2018
Source: New York Post [edited]
https://nypost.com/2018/05/01/coyote-that-attacked-5-year-old-girl-had-rabies/


The coyote that viciously bit a 5-year-old girl at a Westchester county playground before being tackled by a cop was suffering from rabies, health officials said [Tue 1 May 2018]. "We got results back -- and it did test positive for rabies," Catherine Cioffi, communications director of the Westchester County Health Department, told The Post.

The child, [NK-P], had been playing at James Carroll Park in Thornwood with her mom and brother [Sun 29 Apr 2018] when the animal darted at full speed toward them and bit her left arm. The girl was saved from the animal by off-duty local cop Arcangelo Liberatore, who tackled and wrestled it to the ground. The coyote left the girl with a bite wound, her mom with a nip, and the officer with a scrape that came in contact with the animal's saliva.

The injuries could pass the disease to the 3 -- but they all got rabies shots within hours after the attack and will now get 3 more, over a 2-week period, to prevent contracting the virus, according to the cop and the girl's mother. [The girl's mother] said health officials assured her that they'll be fine. "As a mother, you're always concerned about things like this. But the nurse tells us we won't develop rabies if we get the rest of the shots, so that's a good thing," [said the 36-year-old woman].

[The girl] was back at school [Tue 1 May 2018] and doing great, her mom said. "She's been a champ. She hasn't complained once about pain, even when she got the shot [Sun 29 May 2018]," [her mother] said. "She is beyond a trouper."

Liberatore added, "I know that in humans, rabies is an atrocious debilitating disease. My wife is a nervous wreck -- but I'm not concerned about it. I have a lot of faith in the health system," he said. "The nurse I spoke to seems confident about [the procedure]."

Dogs with rabies suffer from aggression and delirium and secrete large amounts of the virus in their saliva, which they can pass to humans through bites and scratches. "Everyone who came into contact with the animal, or its saliva, is being evaluated to determine the need for preventive rabies treatment," the Westchester County Health Department said in a statement. Health Commissioner Sherlita Amler warned, "If a coyote approaches, make noise and try to avoid it. If it appears aggressive or lethargic, it could have rabies, so contact local police."

[Byline: Natalie O'Neill]

