[For details of the coyote attack and the policeman's response, see:
https://nypost.com/2018/04/30/off-duty-cop-saves-5-year-old-girl-from-crazed-coyote/

There is little to add that has not be said many times before. If you are confronted by a wild animal, be cautious, especially if it is a species that is normally active after dark. If concerned, call the local wildlife department so that they can deploy someone to capture the animal and initiate a rabies diagnostic procedure. If bitten, go to emergency healthcare and get vaccinated. Done right it is not a painful shot. And maker sure that children do not, repeat NOT!, pick up any sick bats. Bat rabies is fairly common.

On the other end, veterinarians and wildlife folk should make sure that their rabies shots are up to date. You never know when you are going to be exposed. Since I qualified in 1960 I have been exposed countless times, starting with bats in a volcanic vent in Mexico where they were mining bat guano. And it is a good idea at your annual medical checkup to have them titre your antibody level. Until I was told about the availability of rabies antibody titration, I got my rabies shots every 3 years.

How this South Carolina goat got exposed is not immediately obvious. If it was south of Texas, I would expect vampire bats. Sick bats regularly fall into livestock feed troughs. To keep on top of your rabies get any and all recovered rabies virus strain S typed and map the recoveries if only with coloured pins in a wall map. And remember animals die with a number of diseases -- when an urban population of raccoons grows too dense it is just a matter of time before a raccoon gets infected by a distempered dog and distemper virus moves fast and lethally through raccoon populations. Our last raccoon distemper epidemic killed around 80 percent of the raccoons in the city parish. A raccoon staggering about with distemper is still better checked than ignored. Let the wildlife department decide. - Mod.MHJ]
